article.headline: San Francisco 79, Montana 58
article.story: SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Reserve Johnny Dukes had a career-high 16 points and seven rebounds to help San Francisco win its sixth straight game, 79-58 over Montana on Monday night. John Cox added 15 points, Jerome Gumbs had 14 points and Tyrone Riley scored 12 for the Dons (7-3), who have not lost since Dec. 1. The winning streak is San Francisco's longest since 1999-2000 when it won 12 straight. The Dons, who host Fresno State on Thursday, led by as many as 25 points over Montana, which shot well early but couldn't match San Francisco's depth. John Seyfert scored a career-high 20 points to lead the Grizzlies (4-6). Montana played without Kamarr Davis, its second-leading scorer and leading rebounder. Coach Larry Krystkowiak said Davis was not hurt and had not engaged in conduct detrimental to the team, but did not give any other explanation for why he was held out of the game other than saying it was an internal matter. The Dons won despite being without starting point guard Andre Hazel, who was sidelined with a knee injury sustained in San Francisco's 67-64 win over Pacific on Saturday. Hazel, the Dons MVP in 2003, was averaging 5.6 points and 4.5 assists before getting hurt. San Francisco led by six midway through the first half before heating up from the perimeter to slowly pull away and put the game out of reach. Six of the Dons' first nine field goals were 3-pointers and they connected on 52.8 percent of their shots from the floor in the first half to take a 46-29 lead. Montana shot well early but couldn't keep pace with San Francisco. The Grizzlies missed all five of their 3-point attempts and made only two baskets overall in the final seven minutes of the first half.
